server.py" Documentation Getting Started Guide GitHub edgebitio enclaver Enclaver is an open source toolkit created to enable easy adoption of software enclaves, for new and existing backend Enclaves provide several critical features for operating software which processes sensitive data, including: Isolation: Enclaves guarantee that sensitive data inserted, processed or decrypted can never be read by an attacker and leave the Attestation: Enclaves make it possible to determine the exact identity and configuration of software running in an Network Restrictions: External communication is limited and The network policy is built into the image and therefore the software Enclaver currently supports AWS Nitro Enclaves, with more coming in the Protect your data Encrypt data and protect it during processing Secure your apps Easy toolkit to add security to every layer Add privacy Keep plaintext data out of logs and data dumps Works with Docker Run any container in an enclave Documentation Getting Started Guide GitHub edgebitio enclaver Release Notes Enclaver Enclaver Demos Quick Overview of Build & Run Sample Python App with KMS Integration EKS Cluster with Enclave Node Group Technology: Secure Enclaves Security & Isolation Privacy Attestation & Code Identity An enclave guarantees that sensitive data can never leave the enclave unless specifically Data inserted, processed or decrypted can never be read by an This protection starts in the hardware with isolated RAM, dedicated CPU cores, reduced default networking and Trusted Platform Modules (TPM), all powered by AWS Nitro EdgeBit adds additional network policy that is embedded into the enclave image by the author, so it can t be relaxed or An enclave fulfills the exact definition of privacy: being free from observation or disruption by Even a hostile parent machine can t introspect the enclave or modify its operating Enclaves are the perfect environment to decrypt and process sensitive data of any This can be like a complete microservice or short Encryption key access policies can be tied to the enclave s attestation which guarantees that only trusted code can fetch the An attestation is a reproducable "measurement" of a piece of code that can be used to give the code a unique An attestation can be generated at build time and trusted at runtime by infrastructure Tying credentials or access policies (for encryption keys) to an attestation is extremely powerful because the attestation can t be spoofed or stolen like human credentials or hardcoded Read more about Enclaver attestations . Understanding Identity Governance In appropriate access across digital identities can cause serious breach risks, comprising organization’s security Here is where you require Identity Governance and Administration (IGA) part of your existing IT strategy, integrated with your existing security The Identity Governance program ensures identity and access controls are continuously monitored, maintained and updated in line with the changing business environment and Despite this advantage, many organizations fail to successfully implement Identity Governance program and most of them report lack of a Identity Governance program due to following challenges: Complexity Because identity programs to address complex business needs usually require strong Expertise nature of digital identities and their integrations make it difficult for organizations to identify related Expenditure Identity program is an additional process and naturally demands additional capital While these are the most common reasons, there are also other reasons such as lack of efficient support and proper advisory pulling back organizations from implementing Identity Looking for Support? Subject Consultation Partnership Affiliation Next Copyright © moonrepo GitHub Discord Twitter   Continuous integration (CI) | moon Skip to main content Blog Docs Guides API Packages cli dev report types GitHub Search Continuous integration (CI) Code generation Docker usage Git hooks Open source usage Task profiling Remote caching (experimental) project Sharing workspace configuration Webhooks (experimental) JavaScript TypeScript project references Examples Go PHP Python Ruby Rust Home Continuous integration (CI) On this page Continuous integration (CI) All companies and projects rely on continuous integration (CI) to ensure high quality code and to avoid Because this is such a critical piece of every developer s workflow, we wanted to support it as a feature within moon, and we do just that with the moon ci How it works ​ The ci command does all the heavy lifting necessary for effectively running It achieves this by automatically running the following steps: Determines touched files by comparing the current HEAD against a Determines all targets that need to run based on touched Additionally runs affected targets dependencies and Generates an action and dependency Installs the toolchain, , and npm Runs all actions within the graph using a thread Displays stats about all passing, failed, and invalid Configuring tasks ​ By default, all tasks run in CI, as you should always be building, linting, typechecking, testing, so on and so However, this isn t always true, so this can be disabled on a basis through the runInCI or local tasks : dev : command : webpack server options : runInCI : false # Or local : true caution This option must be set to false for tasks that spawn a or process, like HTTP or development To help mitigate this, tasks named dev , start , or serve are false by This can be easily controlled with the local Integrating ​ Although moon has an integrated toolchain , we still require and dependencies to be installed beforehand , as moon is currently shipped as an npm package . This is unfortunate and we re looking into other distribution With that being said, the following examples can be referenced for setting up moon and its CI workflow in popular The examples assume a package script named moon and are using Yarn 3, but feel free to replace with your chosen GitHub Buildkite CircleCI TravisCI workflows ci.yml name : Pipeline on : push : branches : - master pull_request : jobs : ci : name : CI : ubuntu-latest steps : - uses : actions checkout@v3 with : : 0 - uses : actions setup-node@v3 with : cache : yarn - run : yarn install --immutable - run : yarn moon ci pipeline.yml steps : - label : CI commands : - yarn install --immutable - yarn moon ci config.yml version : orbs : node : circleci node@5.0.2 jobs : ci : docker : - image : cimg base:stable steps : - checkout - node install : : true : 16.13 - node install-packages : : always : yarn-berry - run : yarn moon ci workflows : pipeline : jobs : - ci language : node_js node_js : - cache : yarn script : moon ci Comparing revisions ​ By default the command will compare the current HEAD against a base revision, which is typically the configured (master, main, trunk, etc). Both of these can be customized with the --base and --head options $ moon ci --base < BRANCH --head < SHA Parallelizing tasks ​ If your CI environment supports sharding across multiple jobs, then you can utilize moon s built in parallelism by passing --jobTotal and --job The --jobTotal option is an integer of the total number of jobs available, and --job is the current index (0 based) amongst the When these options are passed, moon will only run affected targets based on the current job GitHub Buildkite CircleCI TravisCI GitHub Actions do not support native parallelism, but it can be emulated using it s workflows ci.yml # ... jobs : ci : # ... strategy : matrix : index : [ 0 , 1 ] steps : # ... - run : yarn moon ci --job $ --jobTotal 2 Documentation pipeline.yml # ... steps : - label : CI parallelism : commands : # ... - yarn moon ci --job $$BUILDKITE_PARALLEL_JOB --jobTotal $$BUILDKITE_PARALLEL_JOB_COUNT Documentation config.yml # ... jobs : ci : # ... parallelism : steps : # ... - run : yarn moon ci --job $CIRCLE_NODE_INDEX --jobTotal $CIRCLE_NODE_TOTAL Documentation TravisCI does not support native parallelism, but it can be emulated using it s # ... env : global : - TRAVIS_JOB_TOTAL=2 jobs : - TRAVIS_JOB_INDEX=0 - TRAVIS_JOB_INDEX=1 script : moon ci --job $TRAVIS_JOB_INDEX --jobTotal $TRAVIS_JOB_TOTAL Documentation Your CI environment may provide environment variables for these 2 Reporting run results ​ If you re using GitHub

Noriware | Impact top of page "Only we humans make waste that nature can t digest" - Ca RSVP Every year, millions of tonnes of plastic enter the environment and cause considerable To effectively solve the problem, it is not enough to start cleaning up, we need to stop plastic production by actually turning off the tab and work together to develop new solutions that will bring positive benefits for our Jul | :00 Venue Name KELP US SHAPE THE FUTURE Kelp = Large coastal seaweeds Together we Our Culture depends on Plastics Plastics have important functions and play major roles in our lives, but their production, use and disposal have countless negative impacts on society and the Due to its seemingly low price, wide range of uses, and great transportation functions, plastic is increasingly being used in millions of As a consequence, plastic production has doubled in the last two Packaging creates a myriad of problems Emissions Plastic as we know it is made from fossil The extraction and processing of these materials is very energy intensive and often raw materials travel long distances to reach the point of During the production of one kilogram of plastic, kg of CO2 is emitted into the atmosphere and after use, the carbon from the end products lingers in our usable environment - in the air, in the soil and in the Microplastic Microplastics are plastic fragments that are smaller than 5 millimeters in size and that are not They are created by the decomposition of larger plastic products through natural influences in our Due to their size and chemical properties, they the human body via air, water and Toxic Substances To make plastic moldable and flexible, additives such as plasticizers and fire retardants are used, which are toxic to humans and These substances ultimately affect reproduction and hormonal control in the They can evaporate from the plastic products or pass into them when they come into contact with other materials, especially fats and Exhaustible & Persistent Ressource The production of plastic uses raw materials that are finite and do not or only slowly grow back and are essential for our In addition, plastics degrade only within 5 to years, depending on the type of plastic and the During this long degradation period, they cause significant damage to our living environment, contaminating other plants and New Problems Emerging From Bioplastics State of the art Bioplastics are either still made from fossil materials or can only be biodegraded in certain environments, such as industrial composting facilities, requiring a lot of time and a lot of Eventually, this means that it still ends up in landfills or incinerators, just like conventional How is generating a new dimension HAS THE SOLUTION BEEN IN THE OCEANS ALL ALONG? WHY IS SEAWEED IMPORTANT? Provide Oxygen Like other photosynthetic organisms, seaweeds produce oxygen as a byproduct of Algae produces to percent of Earth’s oxygen, which sustains humans and other species that live on That’s more than all the tropical rainforests ​ Sequester CO2 Seaweed has already been found in the deep sea, which has absorbed CO2 from the In the sea, CO2 becomes sediment and thus no longer negatively effects our environment, since it is dissolved in seawater and no longer present in the The growth of kelp indirectly binds parts of the CO2 from our Fastest Growing Natural Resource Algae grow ten times faster than land plants, and less than a tenth of the land is needed to produce the same amount of They grow on land and therefore do not compete with other plants for productive They do not require any fertiliser , thus intensive water use is Reduce Pollution By farming coastal areas and discharging wastewater into the sea, algae can help protect the ocean from They can use particularly wastewater to build up In this way, they can also clean water polluted with heavy metals or other substances in coastal areas by absorbing these substances into their Against Ocean Acidification With increasing CO2 concentration in the air, the CO2 levels also rise in the The consequences are that the sea becomes more The acidic conditions then become a stress factor for animals and plants in the The growth of algae breaks down the CO2, thus counteracting acidification and creating a local habitat with a more neutral Resource Seaweeds contain important components, including proteins, amino acids, minerals, lipids, vitamins, fiber and By adding certain varieties to the diets of animals, it is expected to significantly reduce their methane The potential in the food sector is still largely unexploited, especially in Europe, however the demand for proteins is on the ​ ALGAE FARMING HAS THE POTENTIAL TO CLEAN UP THE OCEANS AND THE ATMOSPHERE Algae farms, or algal forests, are underwater habitats that are considered one of the most productive natural ecosystems on They are an important resource for naturally combating the effects of climate change and have positive impacts on a variety of en

Blyss: the store with private reads blyss Docs Beta coming soon The store with private reads Retrieve data privately using homomorphic No PhD Beta coming soon How it works Blyss lets you create buckets, store data in them, and then use homomorphic encryption to perform completely private Nobody, not even us, can learn which items are retrieved from a Blyss Looking up “democracy” in the dictionary, Queries and responses stay encrypted during processing The client encrypts queries under a key only it knows The server never learns what you look up “Sd@f2fsd3” “democracy” “hEa1g9aA7X bN4tl1KvOC” “Government by the ” Read more about how it works The frontier of Build the next generation of Instead of promising not to collect data, guarantee Personalize content without spying on Check binaries against a blocklist without learning Resolve DNS Access blockchain data without leaking Build map apps that don t need to learn user Use IPFS and other P2P services without broadcasting every The cryptographic scheme Blyss uses is and open No NDA to sign, and no "magic" to paper that Blyss is based on Repo with our code Blog post explaining our cryptography Get started in lines of import blyss client = ( "<YOUR API KEY " ) # Access a public bucket for English wiki = ( "wikipedia-en" ) # This read is totally private! # Nobody, not even the Blyss server, # can learn which article you ( "Democracy" ) # You can also create your own buckets, # and fill them with your own ( "us-state-capitals" ) states = ( "us-state-capitals" ) ( "California" , "Sacramento" ) ( "New York" , "Albany" ) ( "Ohio" , "Columbus" ) # Again, this is a completely private read!
